By making the 12 positive, arctan(5/12) returns positive angle rather than a negative angle, but the angle remains the same. I believe he did this to avoid any confusion that might arise from a negative angle. Ultimately, arctan(5/12) will only give you the angle inside the triangle made by the vector components, and you will still need to subtract that from 180 to get the right answer because the vector is in the second quadrant.

You're right, initial velocity in the x-direction is not 0, it is 23 m/s. Initial velocity is only 0 in the y-direction. That is because Vx = Vnet*cos(angle) and Vy = Vnet*sin(angle). The "direction" of the velocity is in a straight line--180 degrees. So, sin(180) is 0 (hence why velocity is 0 in the y-direction) and cos(180) is 1 (hence why velocity is 23 m/s in the x-direction).  I hope this helps!   (Vnet = sqrt(Vx^2 + Vy^2) hence why the net initial velocity is 23 m/s).
